         <h3 id="about-the-edition">About the Edition <a href="#about-the-edition" class="anchor">ğŸ”—</a></h3>
        <p>When â€œThe Decay of Lyingâ€ appeared in Volume IV of Oxfordâ€™s <i>The Complete Works of Oscar Wilde</i> series in 2007, editor Josephine Guy presumed that the fair-copy manuscript delivered to the editors and typesetters of the <i>Nineteenth Century</i> for periodical publication in 1889 â€œha[d] either been destroyed or (more likely) that it remained in private handsâ€ (Guy xl). The manuscript had changed hands at private auctions and sales numerous times over the course of the first half of the 20th Century, but its precise location remained unknown for nearly three-quarters of a century (Bristow and Mitchell 573â€“74).<sup><a href="#note-1" id="ref-note-1">1</a></sup> At the time of the Oxford Editionâ€™s publication, the only known surviving manuscript was the fragmented version of â€œdiscontinuous sheetsâ€ (likely including material from multiple drafts) held in The New York Public Libraryâ€™s Berg Collection (hereafter <i>Berg</i>; xxxvii, xxxix). However, in 2012 the fair copy manuscript resurfaced when University of Akronâ€™s University Archivist S. Victor Fleischer added it to the libraryâ€™s digital catalogue (PR5818.d43 1889). Joseph Bristow and Rebecca N. Mitchel reported the finding in a 2014 <i>Notes and Queries</i> publication and crafted a subsequent print-transcription of the manuscript with an illuminating accompanying introductory essay. They state the manuscript (henceforth referred to as the <i>Akron</i> MS) had actually been donated to the University of Akron in 1962 in the second of two rounds of donations to the Universityâ€™s rare book collection by Herman Muehlstein (574). How the manuscript made its way into his private collection remains undocumented, but it remained â€œundisturbedâ€ there until 2012.</p>
		    <p>As Bristow and Mitchell document, â€œThe absence of the manuscript from the scholarly record and from readersâ€™ perusal means that it has survived in excellent condition, rebound in leather but otherwise untouched. Wildeâ€™s text is written in black ink on fifty-five recto pagesâ€: fifty-four numbered folios with pages labelled 48A and 48B. There are ink and pencil revisions in Wildeâ€™s hand; pencil marks including brackets, strikethroughs, signatures, and punctuation corrections in the hand of multiple typesetters; and sparse blue-pencil inscriptions likely by typesetters are also extant.</p>
        <p>Thanks to the generosity of the University of Akronâ€™s Herman Muehlstein Rare Book Collection, facsimile images of the Akron MS were created in September of 2025. I then converted these images into IIIF format (allowing for zoning and encoding of the images) and created the present edition which tracks the revisions not only to the Akron MS, but also includes versions tracking changes across the initial variants of the essay. This format was chosen for as it enables an easy reading of different versions of the textâ€”and the variants introduced at each stageâ€”alongside dynamic MS images (a uniquely digital affordance). Further detail about the viewing options can be found in the <a href="#using-the-edition">â€œUsing the Editionâ€</a> section below.</p>
        <p>In creating this edition which maps the differences in the texts of the <i>Akron</i> MS, 1889 periodical publication, 1891 version included in the first edition of <i>Intentions</i>, and 1894 second edition of <i>Intentions</i>, I follow the invaluable editorial and critical scholarship of Bristow and Mitchell who transcribed the manuscript with extensive (but not quite exhaustive) notes on variations between the MS and the 1889 publication as well as notable variations from content in the extant <i>Berg</i> holograph. Like Bristow and Mitchellâ€™s editorial contribution, the present edition is not designed â€œto supplant or supersede their account,â€ and I too draw upon both Horst Schroderâ€™s and Josephine Guyâ€™s â€œindispensable observationsâ€ about the essay (99). The work of these four scholars heavily informed the editorial assembly practices and decisions, and their respective commentaries formed the basis of many of the explanatory notes to the reading text. As such, this edition is meant to complement the astounding editorial work of these scholars by creating allowing readers to engage directly with facsimile evidence and explore the untapped hermeneutical possibilities to be found in investigating the essay in its genesis and variations. As an editor, my hope is that The Fluid Text Edition of Oscar Wildeâ€™s â€œThe Decay of Lyingâ€ proves both a valuable research resource for scholars and pedagogical tool for instructors. The goal of this edition is to aid teachers, researchers, and studentsâ€™ engagement with the materiality of textual and literary studies, and the rich interpretive possibilities and insights these considerations afford. My critical contribution based on close analysis of this edition comes in the form of a demonstration of possible uses of the edition and methods of critical inquiry it enables. See the <a href="#analytical-introduction">â€œAnalytical Introductionâ€</a> below.</p>        
        <p><b>A "Fluid Text" Edition:</b><br>
            The term "Fluid Text," â€œany literary work that exists in more than one version,â€ was introduced by John Bryant and taken up (under various nomenclature) by scholars digital editing and criticism such as Paul Eggert, Dirk Van Hulle, and Elena Pierazzo. The fluid or "living-text" (Eggert) concept as an editorial and critical framework theorizes a way of exploring the rich significance in what has previously been termed textual "instability." Bryant offers the fluid text concept and theory as a way of rethinking the â€œwork-concept.â€ Bryant problematizes the notion of an â€œauthoritativeâ€ or â€œfixedâ€ version of any text, the predominant "one-text culture" (Pierazzo) or "single-text logic" (Van Hulle) at the foundation of most literary studies. As Bryant concisely states â€œall worksâ€”because of the nature a of texts and creativityâ€”are fluid texts. . .it is inherent in the phenomena of writing itself. . .Literary works invariably exist in more than one version, either in early manuscript forms, subsequent print edition, or even adaptation. . .the processes of authorial, editorial, and cultural revision that create theses versions are inescapableâ€ (1). Bryant rejects the disciplinary convention of assembling a single critical text because â€œthe smoothness of the reading text, a hallmark of critical editing, in effect denies us an immediate awareness of the actual roughness of the textual record, and textuality itselfâ€ (27). Instead, Bryantâ€™s reframes what has traditionally been called textual â€œinstabilityâ€ as a remarkably generative and rich potentiality for scholarship; whereas textual â€œinstabilityâ€ or â€œindeterminacyâ€ casts the act of editing as an effort to solidify textual precarity, a â€œfluidâ€ text and â€œtextual fluiditiesâ€ not only accounts for, but embraces as a hermeneutically significant the â€œflow of creativityâ€ and the inherently social processes and inflections on the act of writing (as opposed to isolated authorship) (5-6). He argues that the concept of the fluid-text makes room for the taking into account of intention as an utterance of broader socio-cultural movements. Situating his theory in conversation with Foucault and Derrida, Bryant argues, â€œa fluid text bodies forth concrete instances of an idiosyncratic individual negotiating idiosyncratically with an audience. Such idiosyncrasies cannot represent a cultural, but as a particularized instance of cultural engagement, they may be seen in their peculiarity as a concrete enactment of culture. . .they are a graphic manifestation of the discourses of self, word, and societyâ€ (9). </p>
        <p>The approach of this fluid or living text edition is to enact many of the principles of Bryantâ€™s, Eggertâ€™s, Pierrazzo, and Van Hulleâ€™s editorial theories. Putting into practice the idea of multivalent, fluid, and living text, the present edition of Wildeâ€™s edition seeks to direct readers to the realization that texts are yes, authored, but they are also bound up in broader cultural influences and â€œthe socialised circumstances that gave rise to itâ€ (4). For Wildeâ€™s â€œThe Decay of Lying,â€ the most immediate and literally legible evidence of such â€œsocialised circumstancesâ€ is the polyphonic nature of the material folios. Throughout the <i>Akron</i> MS are the pencil marks of typesetters that sporadically mark-up, interject, and augment the text. And their penciled signatures loudly (and far more prominent than Wildeâ€™s comparatively small, ink signature) overwrite fragments of textâ€”taking a vocal, if unseen in print, ownership in and authorial contribution to the essay.</p> 
        <p>As such, this editionâ€™s representations of Wilde's, and other agents, iterative reconfigurations of the essay can and should be read as creative, authorial choices, but they can also be read as acts always inflected byâ€”and discursively engaged withâ€”broader literary, social, cultural, and political moments, movements, and ideologies. As Wilde (drawing on Pater) argues in the essay, Art frames and moulds our subjective impression and interpretation of experience, and in turn shapes and informs the art we create. And in his critical writings, Wilde offers an aesthetic theory that attempts to counter and respond to this aesthetically reproductive cycle, whether through the â€œself-consciousâ€ act of purposeless â€œlyingâ€ or in his philosophies of criticism and the critic (see Danson, Green 399, Riquelme, Small 118-119, and Sussman). Yet his project (evidenced to his use of his own writings and his conceptual similarities to the work of some of his contemporaries as demonstrated by Bristow and Mitchell, Guy, and Schroder), like many artistic and literary efforts of the decadent writers and <i>fin-de-siÃ¨cle</i> aesthetes, is an impossible achievement doomed to failure (even if the attempt is, in the scheme of things, generative). For no artist can ever escape or get outside the cultural and social structures that literally and figuratively frame and shape artistic output. But, hopefully aided by resources like the present edition, we can come to recognize and acknowledge these forces.</p>
        <p>The impingement of cultural and political ideologies upon Wildeâ€™s crafting of the essay can be found in the series of revisions Wildeâ€™s passing references to class.<sup><a href="#note-2" id="ref-note-2">2</a></sup>  Writing of the â€œsilly boys who, after reading the adventures of Jack Sheppard or Dick Turpin, pillage the stalls of unfortunate apple women, and alarm old gentlemen,â€ on f.35, Wilde adds to the MS the phrase â€œwho are returning home from the cityâ€ drawing a clear distinction between the â€œvulgarâ€ boys of the urban London and its upper-class suburban population. Indeed, in the manuscript, Wilde adds the specification that their revolvers are â€œloaded,â€ contrary to Schroederâ€™s contention that this was an erroneous misprint, making clear that the imitating urban boys pose a dangerous threat to suburban population (48). This overt classism is disguised the later variant; the specific reference to â€œsuburban lanes,â€ and the addition of â€œunâ€ to loaded, suggests that these are the â€œsilly,â€ mischievous acts of wealthy middle and upper class, suburban boys who have access to the new, expensive novels (Price, Leah, â€œVictorian Reading.â€ The Cambridge History of Victorian Literature, ed. Kate Flint, Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, p. 40). </p>
        <p>Similarly, on the preceding folio, when Wilde wrote â€œ We try to improve the <s>beauty</s> <b>conditions</b> of the race by means of good air, free sunlight, wholesome water, and hideous bare buildings for the better housing of the <b>lower orders,</b>â€ he originally wrote â€œlower-classes,â€ making clear his association of violence and â€œuglinessâ€ with the lower and working class. However, he struck this phrase, replacing it with â€œpeople,â€ removing the overt class connection in periodical publication (f.34). But when returning to the passage in 1891, he again revised the phrase, changing it to â€œlower orders,â€ again inserting an overt class hierarchy into the passage. With their direct connection to Wildeâ€™s understanding of â€œbeauty,â€ and the assertion that â€œthese things merely produce health, they do not produce beauty,â€ these revisions make apparent a cultural elitismÂ¬ that inflects Wildeâ€™s aesthetic theories. The revised restoration reinserts a differentiation between those who create art and those who consume and are affected by it, as well as the culture of dissensus within the creativesâ€™ space: between realism and what Wilde construes as â€œRomanticism.â€ His articulations of these divisions reveal not just a more pronounced sense of cultural hierarchies that structures the 1891 edition Wildeâ€™s essay, but make clear that they were always present even if not as apparently visible.</p> 
        <p>In Paul Eggert's <i>The Work and the Reader in Literary Studies: Scholarly Editing and Book History</i>, he outlines the limitations of scholarly editing and the production of scholarly editions of texts, arguing for a living model that draws both upon the epistemologies of book history and literary critics for a semiotics and hermeneutics of editing. Eggert's model reads and re-presents texts as socially produced â€œliving worksâ€ or â€œwork embodied,â€ that take into account and attempt to both interpret and present the â€œrelations of documents to versions, versions to works, and works to adaptations. . .â€ and the ways these are â€œplayed out by readers on agented documents, whether print or digitalâ€ (9). His model imbricates literary criticism, editing, book history, and readers. Editors are literary critics that are making a claim about the text in the act of re-presenting it (a claim borne out and evidenced by the editorial choices): â€œthe texts of works never come down to us in unmediated form, every scholarly edition is necessarily an embodied argument about the text or texts of a workâ€ (36). At the same time, critics, he argues, do and should take into account the material and social nature of the â€œliving workâ€ in their readings; and this includes both those that shape the initial production of the text and those that mediate each iteration of in the life of the work in the form of discrete editions of their text. Moreover, in this model criticsâ€™ readings (and any readings) contribute to the aggregation of the â€œworkâ€ as they influence future readings and shape and inform the creation of new â€œtextsâ€ in the life of the work (much like this edition).</p> 
        <p>This edition, then, takes as it's â€œargumentâ€ the position that there is unearthed meaning in the variations that we as readers and critics need to not only recognize but actively engage with during the act of reading and interpretation. The "Fluid Text Edition" of Wilde's "The Decay of Lying" makes visible its growth, multiple variants (each stage), as well as the different hands and processes that participate in literary production; the way written texts also â€œare always evolutionary in their shifting formsâ€ as they, and their meanings, vary and shift as they are â€œredesigned and reprintedâ€ and also â€œrealised by successive readerships.â€ I am under no illusion that this text is not a â€œrepresentationâ€ that is inflected by my editorial and critical positions, which are themselves shaped by the readings of my antecedents. As Eggert notes: â€œTo edit is to mediate, to come between. Documents are not self-declaring and may contain all kinds of impediments to their consumptionâ€ (82). And, indeed, the present edition mediates a number of â€œtextsâ€â€”by Wilde, about Wilde, and about literary texts in generalâ€”to capture a moment of the â€œlifeâ€ of this work. However, in crafting this editorial argument, the edition breaks away from conventional attempts â€œat establishing the texts of works as intended by their authorsâ€ by representing the <i>fluidity</i> of the text and in turn making visible these (re)mediating forces. Additionally, by providing a dynamic representation of the textâ€™s fluid life, the present edition places the reader in a more authoritative (and authorial) position as interpreter and crafter of textual meaningâ€”an active contributor to the workâ€”while also calling to readersâ€™ attention that they themselves â€œare not neutral intermediaries but active mediators of the literary workâ€ (Eggert 15).</p>      
        <p>Moreover, this edition contends that endeavoring to render legible the essay as a fluid text helps readers more easily approach and interpret the â€œmeanings ladenâ€ and latent, â€œin the material forms of the text.â€ (Eggert 3). The methodology for assembling the present edition, with this goal in mind, is therefore more closely aligned with the â€œGerman historical-critical editions,â€ than the methods â€œassociated with James Thorpe in the United States and Philip Gaskell in Englandâ€ for the creation of an â€œidealâ€ or â€œauthoritativeâ€ critical edition â€œemploying copy-texts drawn from a first or a later edition extensively revised by the authorâ€ (45-6). The employed editorial approach leverages the affordances of a digital apparatus to enable and promote access and comparison across variants, recognize the material contexts of production, consumption, and mediation. As Elena Pierazzo points out, a digital environment makes â€œpossible the provision of texts in versions and texts as versions in a way that is much simpler, more intuitive and dynamic than corresponding print attemptsâ€ (49).  Moreover, she asserts, there is resonance between digital and textual â€œmutability,â€ as the digital environment, like the texts a digital edition represents, are also â€œinherently variableâ€ in multiple aspectsâ€”from regular updates, variable user-interfaces, â€œthe possibility of displaying the same text in different ways,â€ and even the dynamic navigation between versions enabled by hypertextuality (58, 50-52). So rather than â€œthe detection and correctionâ€ of what Peter Shillingsburg calls the â€œinfelicities in transmissionâ€â€”the â€œnoiseâ€ or â€œdebris of transmissionâ€ that enters in to any type of communication â€œby the fact that the code of the sender never coincideâ€ and â€œthe medium imposes certain changesâ€â€”Pierazzo advocates for representing these â€œinfelicitiesâ€ (47). This edition does so but is not merely a digital archive documenting these variations. Instead, I contend, it is an edition that, through archival and book history informed editorial decisions in conjunction with this critical introduction and scholarly and critical commentary to the reading text, attempts to help readers realize the confluence of social, political, cultural and material forces that make themselves known through the life and fluidity of the text. While Eggert takes issue with scholars like Frank Moretti and Matthew Jockers on the contention that in the distant reading of metadata/digital texts â€˜their datasets miss most historical connections between literary works,â€™â€ and exclude â€œcontexts of reading and productionâ€ (13), this digital edition attempts to bring these in historical, material, cultural contexts to the fore, and study-able with computational methods, through a restricted dataset representing the work as presented and produced (by readers, editors, etc.) in its initial drafting and three publications. What is rendered legible, then, is how the text â€œlivedâ€ and was â€œproducedâ€ in the contexts of the decadent movement, and the forces these contexts exert on the text which surface in its fluidity (and what remains â€œsolidâ€). The Fluid text edition â€œThe Decay of Lyingâ€ thus demonstrates how â€œmeanings and therefore works were always in process as the network of participants in the workâ€™s trajectory through a culture or cultures across time gave it an ongoing existence: or, what we later came to call a lifeâ€ (15). And taking Pierazzoâ€™s philosophy one step further, the Fluid Text Edition of â€œThe Decay of Lyingâ€ promotes inquiring into the meaning that can be gleaned from the communicative detritus that emerges in any act of (re)mediation and communication. In essence, this edition poses and opens up questions about what can we learn about the transmission of ideas, and the innumerable socio-cultural and political forces that impinge upon this transmission, by the noise that inherently varies and work? Additionally, what might we learn about the nature of literature as medium by studying the variability of the textual medium, the mediation of thought in language, and its various remediations? Finally, how might these aesthetic/literary considerations furnish new critical insights about works/texts, like â€œThe Decay of Lying,â€ that take literary and aesthetic theoretical concerns as their objects of contemplation and the subject that is mediated?  The present edition hopes to not only represent the meaning in the â€œdebris,â€ but accentuate it, study it, and enable critical and scholarly engagement with it.</p>
        <p>John Bryant asserts â€œthe notion of textual fluidity is compatible with current critical approachesâ€ (12), as he argues that â€œthe history of textual versions can be seen as an enactment of deconstructionâ€ with â€œmaterial versionsâ€ and revisions materializing â€œfrom the moment of genesis and on into print, a constant deferral of the literary work itselfâ€ and that â€œanalysis of textual fluidityâ€”writing, revision, and versionsâ€”help us historicize the cultural functionality of creative process: the insertions of self into discourse, the modes of revision, the interdependency of writer and cultureâ€ (10, 12). And this critical compatibility extends to (and is accentuated by) the analytical tools that the digital age and computational methods afford, despite the assertions scholars like Eggert and Pierazzo arguing that Computational Literary Studies (CLS) flatten the fluid, material, and social conditions of the text and presuppose a single, stable text. While admitting that her claim is a â€œcrude generalization,â€ Pierazzo states â€œthat most data mining, distant reading and NLP methods assume texts to be stable, uncontroversial entitiesâ€ and that â€œmoving away from the one-text paradigm may have consequences. . .[for] Corpus linguistics, computational linguistics, stylometry, authorship attribution, data mining and many other scholarly disciplines and methodologies that approach texts from a quantitative point of view are based on the assumption that we can query the one text, and that not only does the one text exist, but also that we know what it isâ€ (56). However, recent work has demonstrated the rich possibilities of combining CLS with approaches that foreground the multifariousness and plurality of the text (e.g. Hurst and Ohge, <i>Textual Cultures</i> forthcoming Spring 2026). And by encoding this edition in eXtensible Markup Language or XML (see <a href="#using-the-edition">â€œUsing the Editionâ€</a> below), the fluid text edition of â€œThe Decay of Lyingâ€ attempts to create a version of the text that accessible to modes of critical inquiry that leverage the affordances of computational and distant reading methods for a historically and materially sensitive reading. Indeed, a close or what Robin Valenza calls "slow" reading alongside data analysis and computational methods can be coordinated and complimentary in ways that can yield new insights about the text, whether through the uncovering of hitherto unidentified or neglected evidence or new readings that the defamiliarized reading perspective engenders. One goal of this edition is to illustrate that although digital humanities, digital editions, and CLS may not be capable of making the material literally more <i>tangible</i>, they can make the materiality of the text, and the theoretical significance of a fluid, polyphonic, and multivalent â€œliving work,â€ more <i>present</i>. Though the digital humanities and book history may seem like polar ends on the spectrum of literary studies, aside from digital archives and metadata, projects like The Fluid Text Edition of â€œThe Decay of Lyingâ€ showcase how their critical interests, methods, and aims often overlap and coincide. </p>
        <p>To summarize, this edition attempts to represent Wilde's "The Decay of Lying" in its initial variants with the goal of enabling readers to view and investigate, through its material forms the hermeneutic significance of text's variability. The variations are themselves utterances shifting a textâ€™s meaning that  may signal inflections of larger social, cultural, or political forces legible in the fluidity of the textâ€™s language. At the same time, I draw on the great scholarship of Bristow and Mitchell, who situate Wilde's printed version and the manuscript in conversation with his notebooks and extensive reading, helping to elucidate what Dirk Van Hulle terms a "creative ecology": "a web of intertextual and intratextual relationsâ€ that includes drafts, notebooks, marginalia, and published variants, â€œpresent[ing] the oeuvre not just as a set of works, but as a Gestalt, as something that is not just more than the sum of its parts, but also different from the sum of its partsâ€ (40, 48). To highlight this network of creative activity, which includes both reading and writing, the fluid text edition promotes users â€œto read across versionsâ€ in a fashion that highlights â€œthe relations between themâ€ and beyond them. To illuminate some of the unseen connections, the edition brings together the excellent commentary and notes of previous Wilde editors Josephine Guy, Horst Schroeder, and Joseph Brisow and Rebecca N. Mitchell alongside my own commentary on the variations present across the earliest extant versions (38). Moreover, as discussed in the analytical introduction below, I attempt to highlight moments of what Van Hulle has called "creative concurrence": the moments of textual and conceptual similarity that emerge across discrete "works" but are a part of the same temporally confined creative activity. Some exemplary instances are discussed below, including those that spotlight the <i>material</i> component of "creative concurrence" as concepts physically and conceptually move across texts, but bleed through and become palimpsestically visible. However, these are not mere moments of practical and/or self-conscious "Self-Plagiarism" (Guy). They illustrate a creative repurposing and re-envisioning of the same literary material in new physical, temporal, and social moments that constitute self-reflexive versions of what John Bryant calls "adaptive revision." Indeed, beyond the external social and cultural forces that become legible through the text and its variants, the internalization and interpretation of these forces and one's own contributions to the milieu or discourse that comprise these larger cultural sentiments are expressed through both revisions and what is left unrevised. And the reader of these texts is both implicated and imbricated in any expression of textual meaning too.</p>
