<p>In a critique of the popular sense of what Art <i>should</i> doâ€”that artâ€™s â€œinterestâ€ and â€œsubject-matterâ€ <i>should</i> mirror the interest of â€œthe publicâ€ and their â€œimmediate-surroundingsâ€ in its contentâ€”Wilde, creating a semantic redundancy for emphasis, reiterates the word â€œshould.â€ But he does so by stacking the terms, one on top of the other, literally mirroring them over the line break. While in any printed edition the repetition works to drive home to reiterative nature of such Art, in the MS this emphasis is materially amplified. The conceptual discussion of art as a mirroring representation of public â€œinterestâ€ and life is materially represented and reflected, materially mirrored, in the very construction of the sentence.</p>
<p>While such moments occur sporadically in the MS,<sup><a href="#note-3" id="ref-note-3">3</a></sup> the dynamic mirroring motifâ€”Wildeâ€™s complication of the relationship between art as representation of nature and/or lifeâ€”arises in its most exemplary material instantiation on <a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f031/f/f031/folio30_fluid/-1/g">f.30</a>. On this folio Wilde wrote:</p> 
<blockquote>To excuse themselves<br>they will try and shelter under the<br>shield of him who made Prospero<br>the magician,Â and gave him Caliban<br>and ArielÂ to serve himÂ as his servants, who<br>heard the Tritons blowing their horns<br>round the coral reefs of the Enchanted<br>Isle.</blockquote>
<p>The mirroring here is even less visible to the reader of any single reading-text edtion, or even the <i>Akron</i> manuscript, than the line break symmetry above. As Josephine Guy reported in 2014, the back of f19 of the <i>Berg </i> MS is a fair-copy of a review for Wyke Baylissâ€™s The Enchanted Isle (titled â€œThe New Presidentâ€ and is quite critical), which came out the same month as â€œDecay of Lying.â€ Both sides carry allusions/direct references to Shakespeareâ€™s <i>The Tempest</i>, forming the basis for her argument that Wildeâ€™s notorious â€œSelf-Plagiarism[s]â€ may actually be a result of complex drafting process where multiple drafts of the same and different pieces were being composed simultaneously. While this may not explain away extensive reusing&#x27;s of whole passages, like the discussion of Balzac on <a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f017/f/f017/folio16_fluid/-1/g">f.16</a> that is nearly wholly lifted from his review published a few years prior, it does suggest an interestingly recursive composition process; a drafting process that would account for the initial reference to Caliban above that was replaced in the 1891 variant. This coinciding of material and textual mirroring physically instantiates the motif, with mirroring allusion on opposite sides of the same material. But in its existence, it complicates the art-nature relationship. Here, it is art that mirrors art, creating a materially and textually self-reflexive literature. Moreover, even when the mirroring effect is physically displaced and obscured through inscription and printing across different materials, its nature as texts gives the mirror, and art as what is mirrored, a temporal permanence that, in Wildes view (as discussed below), eludes endeavors to render art the mirror of life. </p> 
<p>And beyond purely documentary features, what has gone unexplored is how the latter portion of this short piece alludes to ideas about the role and purpose of art, quintessentially decadent notions, that Wilde teases out in â€œThe Decay of Lying.â€ For example, Wilde remarks that:</p>
<blockquote>the pictures of contemporary events, Royal marriages naval reviews and things of this kind, that appear in the Academy every year, are always extremely bad, while the very same subjects treated in black and white in the <i>Graphic</i> or the <i>London News</i> are excellent. Besides if we want to understand the history of a nation <b>through the medium of art</b> <i>it is to the imaginative and ideal arts that we have to go, and not to the arts that are definitely imitative. The visible aspect of life no longer contains for us the secret of lifeâ€™s spirit. Probably it never did contain </i>(3:3).</blockquote>
<p>The review (and many of his reviews Green argues) conceptually mirror the ideas that â€œtrueâ€ art emerges from the â€œimaginative,â€ i.e., â€œlying,â€ and linguistically overlaps with the revised assertion on f.43 and f.44: â€œThe more abstract, the more ideal an art is, the more it reveals to us the temper of its age. If we wish to understand a nation <b>by means of its art, </b> let us look at its architecture <s>and</s> <b>or</b> its music.â€ Whatâ€™s more, the idea of an â€œimaginativeâ€ realism echoes his praise of Balzac in both his review of Lost Illusions, and, in repurposed fashion, in the â€œDecay of Lyingâ€ (delivered via a critique of Zola). Such an example of conceptual resonances nicely exemplifies Van Hulleâ€™s notion of â€œcreative concurrenceâ€ and helps us understand the work as always becoming and inherently â€œsocialâ€â€”in conversation with others and with our past ideas. </p>
<p>Wildeâ€™s writing in this recursive and reiterative fashion, in which he lifts and recontextualizes whole passages, may be a self-reflexive form of the type of â€œcreative synthesisâ€ (Bristow and Mitchell) or â€œabsorptionâ€ and â€œcommunication with styleâ€ (Schiff) that enacts the aesthetic theory Schiff reads in the essay (or a necessity when writing so prolifically). It is not â€œimitativeâ€ but a creative material and conceptual self-reflexivity, creating something new out of the same refashioned material/constitutive parts. Moreover, it demonstrates that textual fluidity is not bounded by a single work-concept, but extends, as Van Hulle shows, throughout a whole oeuvreâ€”moving across discrete â€œtextsâ€ but surfacing on (or through) the same materialÂ¬â€”materially reifying â€œcreative concurrence.â€ Ideas are articulated, rearticulated, reimagined amidst new contexts, even if the words are largely the same.</p>
<p> Indeed, the mirroring of art in art, from one side of the material text to another, not only remains visible across materials, but also frames the subsequent expressions and our interactions with art objects. The material mirroring of content goes beyond a figurative bleeding through, but erupts in content of the passage that follows as Wilde complicates the Art-Nature mirroring dynamic in his reading and interpretation of Shakespeare:</p>
<blockquote>They will call upon Shakespeareâ€”<br>they always doâ€”and will quote that<br>hackneyed passage about Art holding<br>the mirror up to Nature,Â forgetting that<br>this unfortunate aphorism is deliberately<br>said by Hamlet in order to convince<br>the bystanders of his absolute<br>insanity in all art matters (<a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f031/f/f031/folio30_fluid/-1/g" target="_blank">f.31</a>)</blockquote>
<p>And it is perhaps no coincidence that on the following folio of the <i>Akron</i> MS, Vivian declares that Art â€œis not to be judged by any external standard of resemblanceâ€ (<a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f032/f/f032/folio31_fluid/-1/g" target="_blank">f.31</a>). The materiality of Wildeâ€™s â€œself-plagiarismsâ€ converse with the essayâ€™s aesthetic principles to both articulate and demonstrate an aesthetic schema, in which Art does not (re)mediate nature. Rather, â€œthe medium of artâ€ is a structure and structuring force, creating and acting as the framework for understanding our impressions and perceptions of nature (Schiff 90). Our encounters with art create the structure of â€œbeautyâ€ that then frames our perceptions and aesthetic judgements of nature, which are in turn, according to Kantian aesthetics, taken as inherent qualities of the object (nature) itself (what Kant terms â€œsubreptionâ€). And it is this understanding of art that Vivian proffers when he asserts, that art â€œis a veil, rather than a mirror.â€ Art does not reflect beauty in nature but creates the images that we take for a mirror (in ways we do not even recognize). Hence, too, why â€œThe more abstract, the more ideal an art is, the more it reveals to us the temper of its ageâ€ and that great art anticipates life (f.43). Finally, this dynamic becomes visible, as Wildeâ€™s essay demonstrates, in moments of artistic self-reflexivity (mirroring) and the conceptual and material (a)symmetry that arises. Our own subjective positions, and the way art and subjectivity inflect what we assume to be objective, are hyper-legible when art physically and conceptually structures and mirrors itself.</p>
<p>Of course, in Wildean and decadent fashion, Vivianâ€™s seemingly paradoxical aesthetic schema does not remain unproblematic or straightforward. In the MS and <i>Nineteenth Century</i> variants, Wilde would go on to reference Caliban once more, but ultimately revised out the allusion for the 1891 publication:</p>
<blockquote>â€œhis work is entirely wrong<br>from beginning to end, and wrong<br>not on the ground of morals, but on<br>the ground ofÂ Art. From any ethical<br>standpoint it is just what it<br>should be.Â The authorÂ is perfectly truthful, and<br>describes things exactly as they happen.<br>What more can any moralist desire?<br>WeÂ have no sympathy at all with<br>the moral indignationÂ of our timeÂ against<br>M. Zola. It is simply theÂ rageÂ indignationÂ of</blockquote>
<blockquote>Tartuffe on being exposedÂ <s>Caliban on seeing his own face in a<br>glass</s>(<a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f013/f/f013/folio12_fluid/-1/g" target="_blank">f.12</a>)</blockquote>
<p>Wilde changes the allusion from <i>The Tempest</i> to MoliÃ¨reâ€™s <i>Le Tartuff</i>, when revising for <i>Intentions</i>. Guy notes that â€œIn <i>De Profundis</i> and a cancelled draft of <i>A Woman of No Importance</i> Wilde cites both characters as interchangeable,â€ yet, here at least, Calibanâ€™s anger emerges out of self-reflection, a literal looking into the mirror, whereas Tartuffe is exposed by others. One is firmly grounded in an inward-looking act, while the other external. In the dichotomy the essay has crafted, art <i>should</i> expose the self, holding up a mirror to the individuality of subjective experience in an act of self-reflexive, creative â€œlyingâ€ in contrast to an externally focused, mimetic (in someways, Wilde argues, more imitative and deceptive) realism (see Schiff 87). So, while the material allusions are mirrored across discrete texts with shared materials, within the same work the mirroring allusions are ultimately erased, further complicating the art-nature mirroring relationship.</p>
