<p>Although a number of these moments see a reinsertion of the term in the immediate vicinity, the frequent deletions of â€œart,â€ especially during StBa (revisions to the <i>Akron</i> text), indicate a significant reworking of those portions of the essay engaging directly with â€œart.â€ While the initial inclination would be to suggest that this is a product of â€œartâ€ being one of the most frequently appearing words in the text, this logic notably does not hold for the other high frequency terms like â€œnature.â€ Rather, â€œnatureâ€ was the most frequently added word, especially for those incorporated during Stage D (for the 1891 edition) with 16 additions. This contrast increased the ratio of words like â€œnatureâ€ and â€œlifeâ€ in proportion to references to â€œartâ€ over the course of the â€œlifeâ€ of the work. </p> 
<p>Closer inspection of the 16 additions of nature in Stage D shows that 11 of these instances arise in extended passage on Impressionist Art, in which Vivian asserts that it is â€œImpressionistsâ€ who give us the â€œeffectâ€ of Nature, rather than Nature providing the form for the effect of the impressionists. The contention in his aesthetic philosophy that art gives form to our perception of nature, as discussed above, is one that received extensive elaboration over the course of his revisions. Not only does he make this apparent the wholly new passage on the Impressionists, but elsewhere, adding that â€œThe only effects that she can show us are effects that we have already seen through poetry, or in paintings. This is the secret of Nature&#x27;s charm, as well as the explanation of Nature&#x27;s weaknessâ€ (<a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f042/f/f042/folio41_fluid/-1/g">f.41</a>) and</p>
<blockquote>if you desire to see a Japanese effect, you will not behave like a tourist and go to Tokio. On the contrary, you will stay at home, and steep yourself in the work of certain Japanese artists, and then, when you have absorbed the spirit of their style, and caught their imaginative manner of vision, you will go some afternoon and sit in the Park, or stroll down Piccadilly, and if you cannot see an absolutely Japanese effect there, you will not see it anywhere. (<a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f046/f/f046/folio45_fluid/-1/g">f.45</a>)</blockquote>
<p>Wilde is clearly concerned with the distinction between nature and art and, like his removal of explicit invocation of â€œart,â€ systematically eliminates any moments when they become conflated. For example, on <a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f032/f/f032/folio31_fluid/-1/g">f.31</a>, â€œbotanistâ€ is replaced for â€œforestsâ€ and â€œmuseumâ€ for woodland, further solidifying the natural imagery, while in the MS, â€œperfectionâ€ is replaced for â€œresemblance.â€<sup><a href="#note-4" id="ref-note-4">4</a></sup> These efforts suggest that Wildeâ€™s aesthetics are specifically an attack on mimetic Art, an attempt to recapture nature in art. This desire manifests in his elimination of references to â€œphotographsâ€ at sequential stages. At Stage D, he eliminates the reference to the â€œa photograph of a Japanese gentleman or lady,â€ leaving only â€œbeside a real Japanese gentleman or lady,â€ which, in turn, eliminates the sense that photography (as an art) is a representation or an approximation of nature or life. It also removes the possibility that the Realist and Naturalist Arts he takes issue with in the essay is actually a self-reflexive remediation of art, as opposed to a mimetic project. Instead, as a passage from the Berg MS that was not included in the <i>Akron</i> MS suggests, Wilde considered photography and Naturalism to be (erringly) striving after the same mimetic ends: â€œRealism and abandoning the wicked tents of those peripatetic photographers who call them-selves Naturalistic novelistsâ€ (<a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f030/f/f030/folio29_fluid/-1/g">f.29</a>). Indeed, the seemingly increased precision with which Wilde delineates the type of Art he is critiquing extends to his meaning of lying. Realism, in its mimetic but fictional efforts, is â€œlying with a moral purpose,â€ an attempt to replicate Life in fiction, which, with its deceitful intentions (hence, the revision to Odysseusâ€™s â€œ<i>sly</i> words of devisingâ€ <a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f051/f/f051/folio49_fluid/-1/g">f.49</a>), betrays an attempt to recreate or achieve something, rather than: â€œthe only form of Lying that is absolutely beyond reproach is Lying for its own sake, and the highest development of this is, as we have already pointed out, Lying in Art.â€ Again pointing towards the self-reflexivity discussed above, Wildeâ€™s three additions of â€œself-consciousâ€â€”sixty percent of its five total occurrencesâ€”emphasize that the highest form of art should be a â€œ<i>self-conscious creation</i>â€ and not any sort of deluded attempt replicate, remediate, or <i>re</i>present.</p>
<p>The â€œeffectâ€ of these revisions (and Wilde was increasingly preoccupied with â€œeffectsâ€,â€”perhaps the structuring effects of artâ€”quadrupling its frequency from 3 to 13 between 1889 and 1891) in the end, is an increasingly harsh critique of Realism, mimetic art, and Nature in a fashion that amplifies the two prongs of Wildeâ€™s theory of art, as Hilda Schiff describes them: that â€œwe degrade art by asking it to follow natureâ€ and that â€œgood art not only does not follow nature, but nature often appears to mirror art. Believing that things exist only in so far as they are perceived, man&#x27;s perceptions, when loaded with art-images, project upon nature an existence imitative of artâ€ (90). While the latter is articulated in the MS draft in passages like the concluding lines of <a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f055/f/f055/folio53_fluid/-1/g">f.53</a>: â€œThe third doctrine is that Life imitates Art far more than Art imitates Life. This results not merely from Life&#x27;s imitative instinct, but from the fact that the self-conscious aim of Life is to find expression, and that Art offers it certain beautiful forms through which it may realize that energyâ€ and in several revisions, like the Stage D addition just prior to this assertion: â€œLife goes faster than Realism, but Romanticism is always in front of Lifeâ€ (<a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f055/f/f055/folio53_fluid/-1/g">f.53</a>) and the above additions that make the claim explicit (<a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f055/f/f055/folio53_fluid/-1/g">f.53</a>).</p>
<p>However, the former of Schiffâ€™s assertions, and the volatility of â€œdegradation,â€ as opposed to err or fail, might be valuably explored through a form of computational literary studies: sentiment analysis.</p>
<p>A form of Natural Language Procession (NLP), sentiment analysis is a type of text classification which categorizes the words in a text or texts by emotion and sentiment, and in some algorithms assigns a quantitative value according to its emotional valence.<sup><a href="#note-5" id="ref-note-5">5</a></sup> When calculating the sentiment of a corpus, â€œsentiment analysis maps specific words [also referred to as tokens] to specific sentiment values. These values, which are looked up in a sentiment dictionary (or â€œlexiconâ€), range from positive to negative according to the specific design of the dictionaryâ€ (Jockers 160). Â But since in sentiment analysis â€œthe focus is turned away from the actualÂ [content], and more toward the authorâ€™sÂ presentation or organizationâ€Â of the text,Â joiningÂ this analysis with encoded revisions enables investigation intoÂ the shifts in the kinds of textualÂ presentation, the style and tone of the words introduced and removedÂ (JockersÂ 160).<sup><a href="#note-6" id="ref-note-6">6</a></sup> This unconventional method of literary research can reveal hitherto overlooked dynamics and, even when it fails to accurately capture the nuances of language, highlights textual complexities that can be analyzed through close reading. By situating scholars in a defamiliarized position to the textual condition, sentiment analysis and other CLS methods can bring to the fore the rich intricacies at the syntactical and even lexical level. By offering a methodology for studying textual fluidity within the context of creative ecologies and concurrence, such approaches promise to raise important new questions and insights into the complex relationship between material reading practices and composition.</p>
<p>When performing a sentiment analysis on both 1889 and 1891 variants, and tracking how that changes over the course of the text, a clear divergence emerges at what was once the nadir of the 1889 periodical version (Figure 3).  The low point in the <i>Nineteenth Century</i> variant is the Vivianâ€™s recounting of the â€œHydeâ€ like incident, upon revision, with extremely â€œnegativeâ€ words like â€œhorror,â€ â€œterror,â€ â€œfrightened,â€ â€œscreamâ€ and â€œrough peopleâ€ (<a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f038/f/f038/folio37_fluid/-1/g">f.37</a>).<sup><a href="#note-7" id="ref-note-7">7</a></sup> However, upon revision, Wilde flattens the emotional volatility of the scene by adding â€œwell-writtenâ€ and â€œhumanitarian,â€ and through the inclusion of more positive language in the paragraph that follows (words like â€œbeauty,â€ â€œgreat,â€ and â€œfriendâ€).</p>
