<p>Sentiment analysis of revisions, in calling attention to how the presentation of the interlocuterâ€™s discussion changes (for example, Cyrilâ€™s â€œIs that the end of this dangerous the articleâ€ is changed to â€œI like it. Is that the end?â€). And, on the whole, the quantitative results point to key revisions to magnify or add negative language to sharpen the essayâ€™s critique while homing in on the type of art it targets, like the criticisms of Hall Caine, James Payn, and William Black added to the <i>Intentions</i> version of the essay (<a href="https://brandonhurst01.github.io/The-Decay-of-Lying-2025/#/ec/f011/f/f011/folio10_intentions1891/-1/g?zone=%23f055_z001">f.10</a>). Calculating the average sentiment score for each sentence of the 1889 and 1891 variants, indicates that the later variant has on average more â€œnegativelyâ€ connotated language, reflecting the honing hostility of the essayâ€™s rhetoric across variants that can be observed in individual isolations. And, mirroring the refinement of diction that clarifies the type of art to be praised, and the type to be critiqued, the revised criticisms are not only amplified in their emotional valence, but they are also specified to narrow and more precisely defines the â€œimitative artsâ€ it critiques. Thus, in a very Wildean and Paterian fashion, sentiment analysis suggests that across the fluid, living texts, the characteristics of the linguistic <i>presentation</i>, the subject, and the concepts of the argument increasingly align: â€œThe term is right, and has its essential beauty, when it becomes, in a manner, what it signifies, as with the names of simple sensationsâ€ (22).</p>
